Felt personally nibbled considering the theme of my previous NS nation, but oh well. TBH, although I used to view religion as a malevolent belief system detrimental to human progress, I now mostly agree with Pasca's position that God (if exist) is just a source of problem we humans ought to mitigate, and that various belief systems throughout history (communism being a primary example) is already exactly the same as religion. Meaning that this supposed "malevolence" of religion isn't actually that special at all and is nearly unavoidable.

That brings to a common cliche: people basing their nation on their belief systems. TBH, if done right, I think doing this can be a good exercise, considering you have an additional emotional attachment to it — you can view how your views can interact with the world, operate within political power structures, and is perceived by by other population segement of different opinions. Especially if you then arrange for said ideology to fail. RA was basically this at the beginning, although I have now shifted into focusing on establishing a new belief system, as insane as I can rationally get, that I think can be very popular with IRL upper tech sector.

by Kiu Ghesik » Mon Aug 23, 2021 7:28 am

A m e n r i a wrote:
Kiu Ghesik wrote:The only worldview where a nation being antitheistic is a way of making it unabashedly and wholeheartedly evil in the same way that practitioners of chattel slavery are is yours tbh


It's not a worldview, it's a fact. God is the big good, so therefore anything against God is evil by default.

...you are aware what underlying assumptions are, right?

the underlying assumptions behind this statement are that a) god is real, b) your god is real, and c) your god exists exactly as you think your god exists, that is to say, your god's morality is perfect- not an assumption that doesn't logically follow the other two, of course, given that the abrahamic notion of god (a belief i share, albeit christian rather than muslim) positions god as bringer of morality. these are not empirical statements, thus meaning that your claim that your statement is fact is logically speaking bullshit- the foundation of your argument is not rooted in provable fact, and thus there can be no facts proven from it.

discounting that though there is a fourth assumption here that i find pretty much no one but you has posited in the past: that this morality is absolute and extends even into fiction, where by definition there are no rules but what the author of that fiction states to be true. take, for instance, fenexorg, where the god of the setting is definitively malicious, and the protagonist, despite being a terrorist, is a morally "good"- as real as such a thing can be of course- individual with a strong sense of empathy motivated by a desire to rid humanity of what he sees as needless suffering. in that case you'd say that fenexorg is the evil faction for opposing god, which literally no one else here would agree with, i think- though ofc i might be wrong.

or take for instance the lovecraft books (racism aside). are the scientists and professors in his stories the evil ones for opposing the great old ones? there isn't a yahweh there, after all, no "good god"- the gods are if not evil from our perspective distinctly amoral.

or going even further, take the aztec religion, as one of many real life examples- they sacrificed living human beings so that the mother of the chief god in their religion did not overwhelm that god in constant mortal combat and descend on the earth to swallow it whole. to them, not all gods were good guys. i imagine they'd contest your statement strongly.

and this isn't even getting into the other aspect of your statement- the implication that the philosophical position that god as humans conceive it to be is evil is equivalent in moral abhorrence to keeping another human being in a state of absolute subserviance and bondage to yourself and the trading of lives as goods and commodities. one has an active negative impact on the lives of those around you, the other is misotheism.

but that's beside the point. what is the point is that you've taken several underlying assumptions that lie firmly within the realm of opinion or philosophical position and called them indisputable fact, and doing so is... just plain incorrect tbh. within your worldview it may be fact that god is the absolute good, but there are billions of people around the world who do not share that belief, and you've no way to empirically prove them wrong.

tl;dr checkmate libruls
